{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Target head orientation for one slot of a gallery enrollment."}],"sections":[],"primaryContentSections":[{"declarations":[{"platforms":["iOS","iPadOS","Mac Catalyst"],"tokens":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"enum"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"PoseTarget","kind":"identifier"}],"languages":["swift"]}],"kind":"declarations"},{"kind":"content","content":[{"level":2,"text":"Overview","anchor":"overview","type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Used by the Luxand gallery walk to gate per-pose capture on the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"user’s actual head orientation (Vision’s "},{"code":"VNFaceObservation.yaw","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" \/"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":".pitch","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"). Without this gate the SDK would auto-advance within ~50 ms"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"of pose acceptance — the user has no time to physically change"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"orientation, so every captured appearance reflects the same head"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"pose and the gallery gains no angular breadth.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Thresholds were picked to match the user’s normal head-turn range"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"during walking: a low ±7° on the yaw turn poses (Vision compresses"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"physical head rotation, so a larger gate forces an exaggerated turn —"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"see "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"yawThreshold"},{"text":"), and a tight ±5° on ","type":"text"},{"code":".front","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" so it only matches","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"when the user is genuinely centred while still leaving a 2° dead-band","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"below the yaw gate. Vision reports yaw\/pitch in radians (≈ 0.26 rad"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"per 15°)."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Vision sign conventions","type":"text"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","text":" on the rotated, mirrored front-camera"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"portrait buffer ("},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"VNFaceObservation"},{"type":"text","text":" reads geometry from the buffer"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"as-presented to Vision — the selfie mirror flips the apparent","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"rotation):","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"yaw"}]},{"type":"text","text":": POSITIVE = head turned to the user’s LEFT (subject’s"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"POV), NEGATIVE = head turned to the user’s RIGHT. This is the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"opposite of the world-frame “right turn = positive” convention"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"because the front-camera buffer is mirror-imaged before Vision","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"sees it.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"pitch"}]},{"text":": positive = chin DOWN (face tilts towards the bottom","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"of the rotated buffer), negative = chin UP. This is the opposite","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"of the colloquial “looking up = positive” convention.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]}]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/com.youreyeonly.yeofr.YEOFR\/documentation\/YEOFR\/PoseTarget","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"metadata":{"fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"enum"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"PoseTarget"}